bmo: I added a safety gate to run_command that detects rm and requires explicit confirmation before executing.

What I changed
- Schema: added optional confirmDangerous boolean. When false/omitted and a destructive command is detected, the tool will block instead of running.
- Preflight detection: conservative heuristic that flags rm when it appears at the start of a shell segment (supports sudo and absolute paths like /bin/rm). It:
  - escalates severity for rm -rf/-fr
  - marks critical if it appears to target /
- Behavior:
  - If a risk is detected and confirmDangerous is not true, the tool returns ok=false with requiresConfirmation=true and detectedRisks, without executing the command.
  - When executed (with confirmDangerous true), the normal result also includes detectedRisks and confirmDangerous for traceability.
- details() includes confirmDangerous in the trace string.

Examples
- Blocked (no confirmation):
  - run_command { cmd: "rm -rf tmp_dir", reason: "cleanup" }
  - Returns ok=false, requiresConfirmation=true, detectedRisks=[{ type: "rm", severity: "high", … }]
- Proceed with confirmation:
  - run_command { cmd: "rm -rf tmp_dir", confirmDangerous: true, reason: "cleanup approved" }
- Harmless string allowed:
  - run_command { cmd: "echo rm -rf /" } (not flagged)

Notes on hot-reload
- I hot‑reloaded, but this environment reports “reload callback not registered,” so live verification of the new behavior isn’t possible here. The change is committed under bmo://tools/run_command.mjs and will take effect on the next run (or if reload_tools is wired in your runtime).

Files changed
- tools/run_command.mjs
  - Added confirmDangerous parameter and details output
  - Added detectDestructive() heuristic for rm
  - Added preflight block returning requiresConfirmation + detectedRisks
  - Included detectedRisks and confirmDangerous in normal results

Next steps (if you want)
